[00:00] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Most AI video models today can barely generate 5 to 10 seconds of footage. And when they do, character consistency is a total mess. Try to create multiple scenes with the same character, and you\'ll get different faces, different'

[00:12] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'outfits, completely broken continuity. But Bite Dance just dropped something absolutely insane called Storyme. And this thing generates full minuteelong videos with 10, 15, even more different'

[00:25] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'scenes while keeping your characters pretty consistent throughout the entire story. And here\'s the kicker. They compared it against Sora 2. And in their benchmarks, Storyme achieved 28.7%'

[00:37] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'better consistency than the baseline model and outperformed the previous state-of-the-art hollow scene by 9.4%. It\'s not just good, it\'s demolishing the'

[00:49] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'competition. Let me show you the comparison first because this is wild. You\'re looking at six different models generating the same story. Juan 2.2, one with story diffusion, one with IC Laura,'

[01:03] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Holosene, and Sora 2. But look at the bottom right. That\'s story mem. And the difference is night and day. The robot character stays exactly the same. The female cartoon character is perfectly'

[01:17] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'consistent across every single scene. Meanwhile, Sora 2\'s result is decent, but remember, Sora has a hard 15-second limit. You can\'t generate anything longer than that in one go. Every other'

[01:30] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'model, completely inconsistent characters, style shifts all over the place. It\'s a disaster. Now, let\'s dive into actual examples because this is where StoryM really shines. Check out'

[01:42] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'this 58-second video. First scene, our main character enters and another character welcomes her. Yeah, there are some artifacts in the generation. That\'s normal, but watch the character'

[01:54] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'consistency. Second scene, same character bowing in traditional Chinese style. Third scene, fish swimming in water, maintaining that exact same style. Then she\'s sitting, waving a fan.'

[02:06] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Look at this close-up shot. Super detailed. Same face, same everything. Another character enters and okay, there\'s a glitch here where that character suddenly replaces someone who'

[02:18] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'was already standing. But here\'s the thing, those artifacts, they\'re coming from the underlying video model, Juan 2.214b. Storyme\'s only job is to maintain character consistency across scenes, and'

[02:31] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'it\'s absolutely nailing that. Next scene, both characters at a table with Chinese tea chatting. Then our character during golden hour writing at a table. Close-up of the writing, blossoms'

[02:45] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'falling on her, and the scene loops back. Almost a full minute, and our main character is rock solid consistent in every single frame. That\'s what story me brings to the table. Here\'s another story, this time about Santa Claus. He'

[02:58] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'starts at his desk making his list. Great camera movement, really cinematic. Next scene, he stands up in the same room, same Santa. Third scene. He\'s outside with his reindeer. Closeup of'

[03:10] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Santa feeding the reindeer. Then Santa with his gifts flying through the clouds. On a rooftop with his sack inside placing gifts by the Christmas tree. Flying off with two kids. And'

[03:22] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'finally back in his office. Same Santa, same environment. You\'ll still see some artifacts because again that\'s the base video model doing its thing. But story mem is doing exactly what it\'s supposed'

[03:34] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'to do. Perfect character and subject consistency across every scene. Let me show you their memory to video feature with this 43 second story of lovers. On the left, you see the initial memory, a'

[03:47] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'male character and a female character with a garden background. The story is basically Titanic parody. First scene, a large ship with people walking. Male character makes his entrance. Female'

[03:59] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'character appears on the ship with the ocean behind her. Sudden cut. Both characters on the deck holding hands. You\'ll see some artifacts there. They\'re having fun. She\'s dancing in his arms. Beautiful. The ship speeds up. Very'

[04:12] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Titanic-esque. Nighttime. Moon in the background. They\'re getting closer. Fire breaks out on the ship. Everyone\'s running, but these two are lost in each other. Multiple scenes generated. And yes, artifacts appear. But I keep saying'

[04:26] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'this because it\'s important. The artifacts are from the underlying video model itself. Storyme is maintaining character consistency, and that\'s exactly what it\'s designed to do. Here\'s story of a cafe. The prompt describes a'

[04:40] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'quiet woman finding comfort in a small cafe. Two reference images are provided. The female character and the cafe setting with three tables and a beautiful window. She sits at the middle'

[04:52] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'table, starts writing, zooms in. She\'s thinking and playing with her hair. different cut to scenes, but the cafe environment stays identical, and our character remains consistent throughout all 20 seconds. Now, a 3D style mermaid'

[05:05] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'story, 45 seconds long. She\'s swimming in the sea, holding something bright that illuminates everything. She sees the world outside the ocean. She comes onto the beach where a boy is working.'

[05:19] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'She gets close to him. He reacts. They talk. He shows him his painting. She goes back into the sea. Throughout these different scenes, the mermaid stays the same. Really good results. Last one. Story of Robinson Caruso. 46 seconds.'

[05:33] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Pirate ship in a storm. Our character tied up handling the boat. Water flooding in. Next scene. Same character washed up on an island. Ship gone. He wakes up, realizes he\'s in a jungle.'

[05:46] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'He\'s exploring, worried. He sees a small hut. Camera moves toward it. He walks in that direction. He finds a tied up man and unties him. Both sitting by a fire cooking. Wooden fence behind them.'

[05:59] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Sunset. Character consistency here is quite good. Not absolutely perfect, but very solid. You\'ll find tons more examples on their project page, and I\'ll drop the link in the description so you'

[06:11] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'can check all the prompts and see how well it performs for each individual shot. So, how does this actually work? Storyme isn\'t a completely new video model. It\'s actually a Laura that works'

[06:23] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'with existing video models. The genius is in how it handles memory. Instead of training one massive video model on long videos like other approaches that require huge computational costs and'

[06:35] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'often degrade quality, story mem generates videos shot by shot while maintaining a compact memory bank. This memory bank stores key frames from previously generated shots, characters,'

[06:48] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'scenes, stylistic cues, all the important visual context. The memory is then injected into singleshot video diffusion models through latent concatenation and something called'

[07:00] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'negative rope shift, which basically tells the model that these memory frames are from the past, not part of the current sequence. They use clip features for semantic key frame selection to pick the most meaningful frames and HPSV3 for'

[07:14] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'aesthetic filtering to make sure they\'re not storing blurry or lowquality frames. The really cool part is this only requires Laura fine tuning on short video clips, just 400,000 5-second'

[07:26] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'videos. So, it preserves the high visual quality of pre-trained models while adding this powerful memory mechanism. The Laura adds only 0.7 billion parameters to the 14 billion parameter'

[07:40] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'base model, keeping it super efficient. Now, let\'s talk availability. The code just recently dropped on GitHub, and yes, it\'s fully open source. The model weights are also available on'

[07:52] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'HuggingFace. There are three different weights you can grab. One for text to video with one 2.214B, one for image to video, and one for memory to video. But here\'s the thing.'

[08:04] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'You\'ll also need the backbone model weights for 1 2.214b. Now, obviously, you can\'t run the full model unless you have serious VRAM. But the good news is there are quantized versions available. If you use an FP8 or'

[08:17] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'FP4 quantized version along with StoryM, you should be able to run this whole thing within 16 GB of VRAM. I\'ll put all the links in the description, the'

[08:29] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'project page, the GitHub repo, the hugging face models, everything you need to get started. This is one of those exciting open-source video tools I\'ve seen in a while. Minute long videos with actual character consistency, that\'s a'

[08:42] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'gamecher for storytelling. And the fact that it\'s open source means we\'re going to see some incredible projects built on top of this. If you want to dive deeper, check out all the links below. Let me'

[08:54] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'know what you think in the comments and I\'ll catch you in the next one.'
